<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910220-0075</DOCNO><DOCID>910220-0075.</DOCID><HL>   Former Thrift Owner,   Others Plead Innocent   To Fraud Charges</HL><DATE>02/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Robert Allan Ferrante, former owner ofConsolidated Savings Bank, and seven other formerConsolidated officials, pleaded innocent in federal courthere to fraud charges related to the 1986 failure of theOrange County, Calif., savings and loan.   A federal grand jury recently handed up a 31-countindictment against the former officials, including charges ofwire fraud, mail fraud, fraudulent participation in loanproceeds, false entries, bank fraud and false statements.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;This is a politically motivated indictment to seek ascapegoat for the thrift's collapse,&quot; said Brian Lysaght, aSanta Monica attorney representing Mr. Ferrante, 41 yearsold, of Newport Beach. &quot;Mr. Ferrante received no personalgain&quot; from either of two alleged fraud schemes outlined byfederal prosecutors in the indictment, he said.   Mr. Lysaght said the other indicted officials also pleadedinnocent, including Ottavio Antonio Angotti, 54, of La Habra,a former chief executive officer; Ronald Lee Bartholomew, 59,of Corona Del Mar, a former Consolidated attorney; RaymondLloyd Arthun, 42, of Tustin, a former officer and director;and Eric Chess Bronk, 44, of Corona Del Mar, a formerattorney and consultant.   Also pleading innocent were Peter Antonio Sardagna, 47, ofLaguna Hills; William Edgar Crowder, 42, of Covina; andSigmund Kohnen, 43, of Las Vegas, Nev. Mr. Lysaght said aninth defendant, James Charles Allee, 36, of Laguna Beach,Calif., had been scheduled to plead innocent at a separatearraignment.</TEXT></DOC>